{4 Suit Jacoby Transfer - Transfer to Minors}

The transfer to minors can be used for 2 purposes

a) To allow responder to bid 3NT with a 6-8 point hand and a six card minor suit,
if opener accepts the transfer. Otherwise, the contract will be 3 of the minor.|
PG| ***** 128 ***** |


AT|
  
b) To play in 3 of a minor with 5 or fewer points and a six card minor.
^-|
PG| ***** 129 ***** |


AT|^B@2^Y@3
Most partnerships play Jacoby Transfer for major suits. However, Interested players may use Jacoby transfer for the minors as well. First, let me explain the benefits of transfers in minors.|
PG| ***** 130 ***** |


AT|

In general, if you have a weak hand with a long suit opposite a strong hand, it is more desirable to play in the weak hand's suit because in that suit, the long cards will take tricks, whereas in another suit it may not be possible to score the low cards in the weak hand's long suit. The only tradeoff is you have to play at the 3 level, which is kind of high. However, a weak hand with 7 clubs or diamonds the tradeoff is worth it.|
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


AT|

Some partnerships play 2S which is transfer to minors. Opener automatically responds 3C. The partner bidding the transfer passes with clubs or corrects to 3D. That is easier to play, but not quite as flexible. I recommend you start with this simpler transfers and then progress to the stronger and more flexible version which I explain next.  |
PG| ***** 132 ***** |


nt||
 
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
qx||cs|2|at|^-

{4 Suit Jacoby Transfer - Transfer to Minors}

^-|AT|^B@2^Y@3
In the more flexible and powerful version, a 2S bid by responder is a transfer to clubs, and a 2NT bid is a transfer to diamonds. Over each transfer bid, opener has two options to further define his/her holding in the transferred minor suit. Let me explain further.|
PG| ***** 133 ***** |


AT|

Partner opens 1NT and you bid 2S to transfer to clubs. The opener (no-trumper) now can bid 2N which shows 3 clubs to an honor. Whereas bidding 3C denies good club support.|
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


AT|

This is known as a transfer with "pre-accept"  because opener has 2 bids available which can differentiate between good and bad support. As you know the notrump opener does not have such latitude during transfer to majors.|
PG| ***** 135 ***** |


AT|

2N bid by responder is a transfer to diamonds. Similarly, after a transfer bid to diamonds, opener has two bids to better define his/her support for diamond suit. Over 2NT, 3C bid by opener shows 3 diamonds to the A, K, or Q and 3D denies good diamonds. |
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


NT||
 
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
qx||cs|2|at|^-

{4 Suit Jacoby Transfer - Transfer to Minors}

^-|cs||at|^B@2^Y@3

This version of transfer to minor is very powerful but can be confusing because the traditional invitational 2NT bid by responder no longer is available. To make an invitational raise to 2N (since a direct 2N is a diamond transfer), you bid Stayman first and then 2N. Therefore, if responder bids Stayman, on rare occasions she will not have  a 4 card major. You should have a through discussion with your partner if you would like to use this version of transfer to minors.|
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


AT| 

One major benefit of this version is that the partnership  can use it to bid thin 3N games. For example, suppose your partner opens 1N and you have AQxxxx of diamonds and out. You might transfer to diamonds, and if partner bids 3C which shows 3 to the K, you bid 3N since you have a likely 6 diamond tricks.|
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


